issues.body:
### Description

I experience a 500ms wait time in case mongodb server is not running / stopped.
But weird thing is that first request fails in < 1 ms but subsequent requests all take at least 500ms.
It doesn't matter if the php script waits or the request just takes that time. 500ms seems to be some fixed value here.

Please check my PHP script below and try by yourself. No MongoDB server required.
Feel free to add timeout parameters but I didn't had any luck with them.

### Environment

/usr/local/etc/php/7.1/conf.d/ext-mongodb.ini,
mongodb
mongodb support => enabled
mongodb version => 1.2.2
mongodb stability => stable
libmongoc version => 1.5.0
libbson version => 1.5.0
mongodb.debug => no value => no value

### Test Script


```
<?php

function fireAndMeasureTime(\MongoDB\Driver\Manager $manager, $number) {
    $startMicro = microtime(true);
    try {
        $result = $manager->executeCommand('local', new \MongoDB\Driver\Command(['ping' => 1]));
    } catch(\Throwable $exception) {
        echo $number.". query failed with " . $exception->getMessage() . "\n";
    }
    echo $number.". query took " . (microtime(true) - $startMicro)*1000 . "ms\n";
}

// Assuming you have no local mongodb instance running there.
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:3000');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 1); // fails very fast:  < 1ms

// Try to connect to a port running nothing.
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:12345');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 2); // fails very fast too: < 1ms

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 3); // Second request on same port failes after 500ms.

usleep(200*1000); // it doesn't matter where the 500ms above are spent, so spend some in php to show effect.

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 4); // ~300ms only because we waited 200 ms before

// switch port back and forth
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:3000');
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:12345');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 5); // still slow, as if the 500ms wait time is required.

// switch back to first connection (has been used more than 500ms ago)
$manager = new \MongoDB\Driver\Manager('mongodb://127.0.0.1:3000');

fireAndMeasureTime($manager, 6); // fast again, 500ms wait window is over on this connection.

```

Outpout:

```
1. query failed with No suitable servers found (`serverSelectionTryOnce` set): [connection refused calling ismaster on '127.0.0.1:3000']
1. query took 0.65803527832031ms
2. query failed with No suitable servers found (`serverSelectionTryOnce` set): [connection refused calling ismaster on '127.0.0.1:12345']
2. query took 0.1680850982666ms
3. query failed with No suitable servers found (`serverSelectionTryOnce` set): [connection refused calling ismaster on '127.0.0.1:12345']
3. query took 505.54895401001ms
4. query failed with No suitable servers found (`serverSelectionTryOnce` set): [connection refused calling ismaster on '127.0.0.1:12345']
4. query took 297.63507843018ms
5. query failed with No suitable servers found (`serverSelectionTryOnce` set): [connection refused calling ismaster on '127.0.0.1:12345']
5. query took 500.42200088501ms
6. query failed with No suitable servers found (`serverSelectionTryOnce` set): [connection refused calling ismaster on '127.0.0.1:3000']
6. query took 0.04887580871582ms
```

### Expected and Actual Behavior

Actual: See output above, long wait time before errors happen.

Expected: Always fail immediately or fail after some configurable timeout < 500ms

Hy anyone,

I create new connection to mongodb from php7 
but I get error : **"authectication fail"** 

this script create new connection :

$conn = new Client("mongodb://user:password@host:port");
$db = $conn->selectDatabase("DATABASE_NAME");
$collection = $db->selectCollection("COLLECTION_NAME");
$data = $collection->find();

Is there a solution to my problem ? Is there anybody who can help me ?

We can discuss via email, this my email karsaaif87@gmail.com

Thank you,

I won't go into the details but due to a combination of our application not handling utf16 pairs correctly, the non-strictness of json_decode and the old mongo php driver not caring about invalid utf8 sequences, our production DB has a fair bit of documents that cannot be handled by the new mongo php driver.

Simple test script to get you setup with a "broken" document; it does a write and a read with the new and old drivers to illustrate what happens.
```
<?php
    $prefix = "{\"value\":\"";
    $postfix = "\"}";
    $testString = "\\ud83c \\udd71";
    $testString = "$prefix$testString$postfix";
    $testString = json_decode($testString, true)["value"];

    $updateCriteria = ["_id" => "corrupt bson"];
    
    $mongoManager = new MongoDB\Driver\Manager();
    
    try
    {
        $bulk = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite();
        $bulk->update($updateCriteria, ['$set' => ["TestStringNew" => $testString]], ["upsert" => true]);
        $result = $mongoManager->executeBulkWrite("database.collection", $bulk);
        
        if($result->getMatchedCount() == 0)
        {
            print("Couldn't update account\n");
        }
        else
        {
            print("Update success\n");
        }
    }
    catch(MongoDB\Driver\Exception\Exception $e)
    {
        echo get_class($e), ": ", $e->getMessage(), " - ", $e->getCode(), "\n";
    }
        
    print("Update with old driver:\n");
    
    $legacyClient = new MongoClient();
    
    try
    {
        $result = $legacyClient->database->collection->update($updateCriteria, ['$set' => ["TestStringOld" => $testString]], ["upsert" => true]);
        if(isset($result['err']) || $result['n'] == 0)
        {
            print("Couldn't update account\n");
        }
        else
        {
            print("Update success\n");
        }
    }
    catch(MongoException $e)
    {
        echo get_class($e), ": ", $e->getMessage(), " - ", $e->getCode(), "\n";
    }
    
    print("Find with new driver:\n");
    
    try
    {
        $query = new MongoDB\Driver\Query($updateCriteria, ["projection" => ["TestStringNew" => true, "TestStringOld" => true]]);
        $cursor = $mongoManager->executeQuery("database.collection", $query);
        foreach($cursor as $account)
        {
            print(json_encode($account));
            print("\n");
        }
    }
    catch(MongoDB\Driver\Exception\Exception $e)
    {
        echo get_class($e), ": ", $e->getMessage(), " - ", $e->getCode(), "\n";
    }
    
    print("Find with old driver:\n");
    
    try
    {
        $account = $legacyClient->database->collection->findOne($updateCriteria, ["TestStringOld" => true, "TestStringNew" => true]);
        if(is_null($account))
        {
            print("null account?");
        }
        else
        {
            var_dump($account);
        }
    }
    catch(MongoException $e)
    {
        echo get_class($e), ": ", $e->getMessage(), " - ", $e->getCode(), "\n";
    }
?>
```

The output when trying to write with the new driver will give something like `MongoDB\Driver\Exception\UnexpectedValueException: Got invalid UTF-8 value serializing '��� ���'` which isn't super duper helpful if you don't already know what's wrong but it at least tries to print the unexpected value for my debugging pleasure.

The output when trying to read with the new driver will give something like
`MongoDB\Driver\Exception\UnexpectedValueException: Detected corrupt BSON data`. Note that the unexpected value is not printed at all. For large documents it can be quite time consuming to try and figure out where the invalid UTF8 is. I propose enhancing this error message like `Detected corrupt BSON data while deserializing property 'FirstThing.SecondThing.Whatever'`

Some commands return additional information when encountering an error. In this specific case, the `shardCollection` command contains a list of indexes and a proposed key in its result if the shard key is not already present as an index:

```
mongos> db.adminCommand({shardCollection: 'doctrine_odm_tests.sharded.one', key: { k: 1 }})
{
    "proposedKey" : {
        "k" : 1
    },
    "curIndexes" : [
        {
            "v" : 1,
            "key" : {
                "_id" : 1
            },
            "name" : "_id_",
            "ns" : "doctrine_odm_tests.sharded.one"
        }
    ],
    "ok" : 0,
    "errmsg" : "please create an index that starts with the shard key before sharding."
}
```

However, when running this command through the driver, the resulting `MongoDB\Driver\Exception\RuntimeException` does not contain the `proposedKey` and `curIndexes` fields. This makes it impossible to use the command result to get the proper index one should create for the shard key.

